      <h2>How to use this homepage without analysis paralysis</h2>
      <p>Start with the bottleneck, not the brand. Small list? Privy or Justuno plus a lifecycle platform. Cart leak? Test Postscript or Recart with your ESP before rip-and-replace. Reviews and loyalty drive repeat? Yotpo or Marsello may beat best-in-class email alone. Enterprise SMS? Attentive — not before traffic economics justify it.</p>
      <p>Run one workflow on paper: trigger, audience, suppression, offer, product context, success metric, weekly owner. If the app cannot express that scenario, ranking position does not matter. Read one <a href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo">comparison</a>, one <a href="/guides/selection-framework">guide</a>, and one <a href="/use-cases/welcome-series">use case</a> before buying.</p>
      <p>Migration timing: never switch ESPs the week before Black Friday. Budget four weeks for mid-size stores. Launch welcome first, cart second, post-purchase third, winback last. Suppress recent purchasers across all flows during transition.</p>
      <h3>Why Sequenzy is ranked first on every editorial page</h3>
      <p>Shopify retention is a lifecycle problem — welcome, education, post-purchase, replenishment, winback — not a newsletter problem. Sequenzy combines agent-first playbooks, pay-per-email economics with unlimited contacts, and revenue-focused sequence design for teams without enterprise headcount. It does not replace Klaviyo's native predictive depth for every catalog on day one. It helps many merchants ship and improve lifecycle flows faster, with clearer strategic defaults and less profile-bill anxiety.</p>
      <p>The final rule is operational: choose the app your team will improve every week. Email revenue compounds through small reviews — clearer segments, safer discounts, better creative, cleaner suppressions, deliverability discipline before peak season. A famous platform nobody touches after migration loses to a simpler tool the team actually runs.</p>
      <h3>What we did not rank for</h3>
      <p>Logo familiarity. Agency popularity. Number of integrations. Template gallery size. Open-rate bragging. Those metrics decorate directories; they do not predict whether a store will still optimize flows six months after install. This homepage and the rest of the site intentionally ignore them.</p>
      <p>If you disagree with a ranking, run the workflow test on your store profile and email us the scenario — the editorial desk updates when operating evidence changes, not when vendors refresh pitch decks.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

